utils
Class PairIntDouble

java.lang.Object
  utils.PairIntDouble
All Implemented Interfaces:
java.lang.Comparable, java.io.Serializable
public class PairIntDouble
extends java.lang.Object
implements java.lang.Comparable, java.io.Serializable

utility class with the same semantics as the Pair class, but restricted so that the first object in the Pair is an int and the second a double. Also, it implements the Thread-Local Object Pool mechanism for significantly reducing new object allocations (especially useful in multi-threaded contexts.) However, it becomes the responsibility of the programmer to always call release() on an object that is no longer needed to free-up objects in the pool, otherwise, the pool will soon be exhausted, and when new objects are needed, a call to new PairIntDouble(i,val) will occur each time afterwards.

newInstance

public static PairIntDouble newInstance(int i,
                                        double val)
returns a managed object if space exists for the current thread, else creates a new unmanaged object. This method forms the only public interface method for getting a new object (the programmer has no control over whether the object will come from the current thread's local pool or via a call to new PairIntDouble(i,val);.)
